<TITLE> Shafique hopes war crimes trial will start in a month </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 9 (bdnews24.com)Law minister Shafique Ahmed is hopeful that the trial of war crimes will start within a month and said the parliament will pass the related act into law on Thursday. "The 1973 International Crimes (Tribunal) Act has been amended to keep the war crimes trial beyond question. It will be passed in parliament today," he told reporters at the Secretariat. The appointment of the investigation agency and prosecution team and some other preparations will be hopefully be done in a month to start the trial, Shafique added. "Amendment was brought to the law to ensure fair and neutral trial and to make them globally acceptable. Any individual or political group will not be politically persecuted under the newly amended act." The minister said a tribunal will be formed for the trial . A law ministry official had told bdnews24.com that the draft amendment also proposed to reform the definition of "associate force" to include groups such as the local Rajakar, Al Badr and Al Shams militias who collaborated with the Pakistani occupying forces in 1971. Trial of war crimes, perpetrated during the Bangladesh's war of independence from Pakistan in 1971, was one of the election pledges of the present Awami League government. A resolution to try war criminals was passed in January during the first session of the new parliament. bd
